e":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Whitley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the many places called Whitley (in Yorkshire, Cheshire, Northumberland, Wiltshire, Warwickshire), Whiteley, or Whitleigh (in Berkshire). The placename is common, generally with the meaning ‘white clearing’ (Old English <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’), or occasionally ‘wheat clearing’ (Old English <i>hwǣte</i> + <i>lēah</i>). According to Redmonds, the Yorkshire surname originated in a locality in the Elland area, perhaps White Lee in Scammonden or White Lee in Mytholmroyd."],"variants":[{"name":"Whitledge","meanings":["English: perhaps from an unidentified or lostplacename, or an arbitrarily altered form of   Whitley  ."]},{"name":"Whitely","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Whitley  ."]},{"name":"Whitler","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of <b>Whit(t)la</b>, itself avariant of   Whitley  ."]},{"name":"Whiteley","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Whitley  ."]},{"name":"Whittley","meanings":["English: variant of   Whitley  ."]}]},{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":32,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":63,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":88,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":